{"title_page": "Irrfan Khan filmography", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n[[File:Irrfan Khan 2012.jpg|thumb|upright=1|Khan in 2012]]\n'''Sahabzade Irfan Ali Khan''' (7 January 1966 {{en dash}} 29 April 2020), credited as '''[[Irrfan Khan]]''' or simply '''Irrfan''', was an [[Indian film]] actor, known for his work predominantly in [[Hindi cinema]], as well as his works in [[Cinema of the United Kingdom|British films]] and [[Hollywood]].<ref name=\"Irrfan drops Khan\">{{cite web |url=http://news.avstv.com/2012/03/07/irrfan-drops-khan/ |title=Irfan drops 'Khan{{'-}} |publisher=News.avstv.com |accessdate=2012-07-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927162036/http://news.avstv.com/2012/03/07/irrfan-drops-khan/ |archivedate=27 September 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Jha |first=Subhash K |url=http://www.mid-day.com/entertainment/2012/mar/070312-Irrfan-drops-his-surname-Khan.htm |title=Irrfan drops his surname Khan |publisher=Mid-day.com |date=7 March 2012 |accessdate=2012-07-21}}</ref> He made his screen debut with the [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nominated film ''[[Salaam Bombay!]]'' (1988). Followed by a series of roles in films that failed to propel his career forward, he received critical acclaim for playing negative roles in the [[Drama Film|drama]] films ''[[Haasil]]'' (2003) and ''[[Maqbool]]'' (2004), for the former he won the [[Filmfare Award for Best Performance in a Negative Role|Filmfare Award for Best Villain]]. The successful drama ''[[Life in a... Metro]]'' (2007) marked a turning point in Khan's career, earning him praise and several awards including the [[Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actor]]. He rose to prominence with his portrayal of [[Paan Singh Tomar]] in the acclaimed [[Biographical film|biographical]] sports drama ''[[Paan Singh Tomar (film)|Paan Singh Tomar]]'' (2011), which garnered him the [[National Film Award for Best Actor]] and a [[Filmfare Critics Award for Best Actor]].<ref name=\"60thaward\">{{cite press_release |title=60th National Film Awards Announced |url=http://pib.nic.in/archieve/others/2013/mar/d2013031801.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=Press Information Bureau (PIB), India |accessdate=18 March 2013}}</ref> His performance in the [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA Award]] nominated romance ''[[The Lunchbox]]'' (2013) earned him universal acclaim by the critics and audiences. Khan went on to feature in the commercially and critically successful films ''[[Haider (film)|Haider]]'' (2014), ''[[Gunday]]'' (2014), ''[[Piku]]'' (2015) and ''[[Talvar (film)|Talvar]]'' (2015). His highest-grossing Hindi release came with the critically acclaimed [[comedy-drama]] ''[[Hindi Medium]]'' (2017), which became a sleeper hit in [[India]] and [[China]], which ranks among [[List of highest-grossing Indian films|highest-grossing Indian films of all time]] and earned him praise for his performance, winning several awards including the [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor]].\n\nGlobally, Khan had worked in several international projects such as ''[[The Warrior (2001 British film)|The Warrior]]'' (2001), ''[[The Namesake (film)|The Namesake]]'' (2006), ''[[The Darjeeling Limited]]'' (2007), the Academy Award winning film ''[[Slumdog Millionaire]]'' (2008), ''[[New York, I Love You]]'' (2009), ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man (2012 film)|The Amazing Spider-Man]]'' (2012), ''[[Life of Pi (film)|Life of Pi]]'' (2012), ''[[Jurassic World]]'' (2015) and ''[[Inferno (2016 film)|Inferno]]'' (2016). As of 2017, his films have grossed {{US$|3.643 billion|link=yes}} at the worldwide box office.<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web|title=Irrfan Khan Movie Box Office Results|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?view=Actor&id=irrfankhan.htm|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|year=2017|accessdate=7 April 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Film==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" width=80%\n!scope=\"col\" width=\"10%\"| Year\n!scope=\"col\"| Title\n!scope=\"col\"| Role\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n!scope=\"col\" width=\"10%\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| 1988 || ''[[Salaam Bombay!]]''|| Letter writer || ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" | 1989 || ''[[Kamla Ki Maut]]'' || Ajit || ||\n|-\n| ''Jazeere'' || Alfred || ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" | 1990 || ''[[Drishti (film)|Drishti]]'' || Rahul || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Ek Doctor Ki Maut]]'' || Amulya || ||\n|-\n| 1991 || ''Pita (The Father)'' || Dr.Sen || ||\n|-\n| 1992 || ''Mujhse Dosti Karoge'' || Mir Hassan || ||<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultraindia.com/film-details/4829-mujhse-dosti-karoge |title=Mujhse Dosti Karoge - 1992 |publisher=Ultra India}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1993 || ''Karamati Coat'' || Jaggu || ||<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/happy-birthday-irrfan-khan-5013880/ |title=Happy birthday Irrfan: The actor whose skills escape definition |publisher=[[The Indian Express]]}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1994 || ''[[The Cloud Door]]'' ||  Irfan ||\n|-\n| ''Purush'' ||  || ||\n|-\n| 1998 || ''[[Bada Din]]'' ||  Police Inspector || ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2000 || ''[[The Goal (film)|The Goal]]'' (Hindi) ||  Anupam Singh ||\n|-\n|| ''[[Ghaath]]'' || Mamu / Romesh Bhagwat Dogra || ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2001|| ''[[The Warrior (2001 British film)|The Warrior]]'' || Lafcadia \u2013 Warrior ||  ||\n|-\n| ''[[Kasoor]]'' || Public Prosecutor Nitin Mehta || ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"| 2002\n| ''Bokshu, The Myth'' || High priest (Tantric yogi) || Indian English film\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2006/film/markets-festivals/bokshu-the-myth-1200515561/|title=Bokshu, The Myth|last=Young|first=Deborah|date=13 June 2006|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=18 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2002/may/22sen.htm|title=Why can't an Indian make a film in English?|last=Warrier|first=Shobha|date=22 May 2002|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|acces