\"3\"| 2016 || ''[[The Jungle Book (2016 film)|The Jungle Book]]'' || [[Baloo]] (voice) || Hindi dub ||\n|-\n| ''[[Inferno (2016 film)|Inferno]]'' || Harry \"The Provost\" Sims || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Madaari]]'' || Nirmal Kumar || ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"| 2017 || ''[[Hindi Medium (film)|Hindi Medium]]''  || Raj Batra || || \n|-\n| ''[[Doob: No Bed of Roses]]'' || Javed Hasan || [[Indo-Bangla joint production|Bangladesh-India]] joint venture film || \n|-\n| ''[[The Song of Scorpions]]'' || Aadam || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Qarib Qarib Singlle]]'' || Yogi || ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 2018 || ''[[Blackmail (2018 film)|Blackmail]]'' || Dev Kaushal || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Puzzle (2018 film)|Puzzle]]'' || Robert ||English movie \n|\n|-\n| ''[[Karwaan (film)|Karwaan]]'' || Shaukat || ||\n|-\n| 2020 || ''[[Angrezi Medium]]'' || Champak Bansal || ||<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/taran_adarsh/status/1114009094547841024|title=Irrfan Khan resumes work... #AngreziMedium shooting begins in #Udaipur today [5 April 2019]... Directed by Homi Adajania... Produced by Dinesh Vijan... Will be shot in #Udaipur and #London... #AngreziMedium is the sequel to the smash hit #HindiMedium, but with a new story.|last=adarsh|first=taran|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Television==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Year !! Show !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n|1985\u20131986\n|''[[Shrikant (TV show)|Shrikant]]''\n|\n|\n|-\n|1988\n|''[[Bharat Ek Khoj]]''\n|[[Abd al-Qadir Bada'uni]]\n|Episodes 32 and 33.\n|-\n|1991\n|[[Kahkashan]]\n|\n|\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[Chanakya (TV series)|Chanakya]]''\n|\"Senapati\" Bhadrashal\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1993\n|''Shesh Prashn''\n|Shivnaath\n|\n|-\n|[[kirdaar]]\n|\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1994\n|''[[Chandrakanta (TV series)|Chandrakanta]]''\n|\"Badrinath / Somnath\"\n|\n|-\n|''[[The Great Maratha]]''\n|[[Najib-ud-daula]] and Gulam Kadir Khan\n|\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Banegi Apni Baat]]''\n| Kumar\n|\n|-\n|1995\u20131996\n|''Darr''\n|Serial killer\n|\n|-\n| 1996\n|''[[Just Mohabbat]]''\n|\"Mr. Singh\" \n| Episodes 4 and 5<ref>{{cite web|title=Just Mohabbat: Episode 4, from SET India official Youtube channel|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=luj495o6X0o}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1997\n|''[[Jai Hanuman]]''\n|[[Maharishi Valmiki]]\n|\n|-\n|''Bombay Blue''\n| Rameez\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|Sparsh\n|\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Star Bestsellers]]''\n|\n| Episode \"Ek Shaam Ke Mulaqaat\"\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[Ssshhhh...Koi Hai]]''\n| Amar\n| Episode 9 (Mumkin)<ref>{{cite web|title=Ssshhhh...Koi Hai: Episode 9, from HOTSTAR Official Website|url=https://www.hotstar.com/tv/ssshhhhkoi-hai/s-2097/from-reel-to-real/1000234010}}</ref>\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Kyaa Kahein]]''\n|Host\n|\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[Mano Ya Na Mano (2006 TV series)|Mano Ya Na Mano]]''\n|Host\n|\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[Don (TV series)|Don]]''\n|Host\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[MTV Roadies 7.0|MTV Hero Honda Roadies 7]]''\n|Himself\n|\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[In Treatment (U.S. TV series)|In Treatment]]''\n|Sunil\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Tokyo Trial (miniseries)|Tokyo Trial]]''\n|[[Radhabinod Pal]]\n|\n|}\n\n==Video games==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Show !! Voice role !! Notes\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Lego Jurassic World]]''\n| Simon Masrani \n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Lego Dimensions]]''\n| Simon Masrani \n|\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khan, Irrfan}}\n[[Category:Indian filmographies]]\n[[Category:Actor filmographies]]\n[[Category:Male actor filmographies]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n[[File:Irrfan Khan 2012.jpg|thumb|upright=1|Khan in 2012]]\n'''Sahabzade Irfan Ali Khan''' (7 January 1966 {{en dash}} 29 April 2020), credited as '''[[Irrfan Khan]]''' or simply '''Irrfan''', was an [[Indian film]] actor, known for his work predominantly in [[Hindi cinema]], as well as his works in [[Cinema of the United Kingdom|British films]] and [[Hollywood]].<ref name=\"Irrfan drops Khan\">{{cite web |url=http://news.avstv.com/2012/03/07/irrfan-drops-khan/ |title=Irfan drops 'Khan{{'-}} |publisher=News.avstv.com |accessdate=2012-07-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927162036/http://news.avstv.com/2012/03/07/irrfan-drops-khan/ |archivedate=27 September 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Jha |first=Subhash K |url=http://www.mid-day.com/entertainment/2012/mar/070312-Irrfan-drops-his-surname-Khan.htm |title=Irrfan drops his surname Khan |publisher=Mid-day.com |date=7 March 2012 |accessdate=2012-07-21}}</ref> He made his screen debut with the [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nominated film ''[[Salaam Bombay!]]'' (1988). Followed by a series of roles in films that failed to propel his career forward, he received critical acclaim for playing negative roles in the [[Drama Film|drama]] films ''[[Haasil]]'' (2003) and ''[[Maqbool]]'' (2004), for the former he won the [[Filmfare Award for Best Performance in a Negative Role|Filmfare Award for Best Villain]]. The successful drama ''[[Life in a... Metro]]'' (2007) marked a turning point in Khan's career, earning him praise and several awards including the [[Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actor]]. He rose to prominence with his portrayal of [[Paan Singh Tomar]] in the acclaimed [[Biographical film|biographical]] sports drama ''[[Paan Singh Tomar (film)|Paan Singh Tomar]]'' (2011), which garnered him the [[National Film Award for Best Actor]] and a [[Filmfare Critics Award for Best Actor]].<ref name=\"60thaward\">{{cite press_release |title=60th National Film Awards Announced |url=http://pib.nic.in/archieve/others/2013/mar/d2013031801.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=Press Information Bureau (PIB), India |accessdate=18 March 2013}}</ref> His performance in the [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA Award]] nominated romance ''[[The Lunchbox]]'' (2013) earned him universal acclaim by the critics and audiences. Khan went on to feature in the commercially and critically successful films ''[[Haider (film)|Haider]]'' (2014), ''[[Gunday]]'' (2014), ''[[Piku]]'' (2015) and ''[[Talvar (film)|Talvar]]'' (2015). His highest-grossing Hindi release came with the critically acclaimed [[comedy-drama]] ''[[Hindi Medium]]'' (2017), which became a sleeper hit in [[India]] and [[China]], which ranks among [[List of highest-grossing Indian films|highest-grossing Indian films of all time]] and earned him praise for his performance, winning several awards including the [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor]].\n\nGlobally, Khan had worked in several international projects such as ''[[The Warrior (2001 British film)|The Warrior]]'' (2001), ''[[The Namesake (film)|The Namesake]]'' (2006), ''[[The Darjeeling Limited]]'' (2007), the Academy Award winning film ''[[Slumdog Millionaire]]'' (2008), ''[[New York, I Love You]]'' (2009), ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man (2012 film)|The Amazing Spider-Man]]'' (2012), ''[[Life of Pi (film)|Life of Pi]]'' (2012), ''[[Jurassic World]]'' (2015) and ''[[Inferno (2016 film)|Inferno]]'' (2016). As of 2017, his films have grossed {{US$|3.643 billion|link=yes}} at the worldwide box office.<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web|title=Irrfan Khan Movie Box Office Results|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?view=Actor&id=irrfankhan.htm|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|year=2017|accessdate=7 April 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Film==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" width=80%\n!scope=\"col\" width=\"10%\"| Year\n!scope=\"col\"| Title\n!scope=\"col\"| Role\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n!scope=\"col\" width=\"10%\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| 1988 || ''[[Salaam Bombay!]]''|| Letter writer || ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" | 1989 || ''[[Kamla Ki Maut]]'' || Ajit || ||\n|-\n| ''Jazeere'' || Alfred || ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" | 1990 || ''[[Drishti (film)|Drishti]]'' || Rahul || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Ek Doctor Ki Maut]]'' || Amulya || ||\n|-\n| 1991 || ''Pita (The Father)'' || Dr.Sen || ||\n|-\n| 1992 || ''Mujhse Dosti Karoge'' || Mir Hassan || ||<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultraindia.com/film-details/4829-mujhse-dosti-karoge |title=Mujhse Dosti Karoge - 1992 |publisher=Ultra India}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1993 || ''Karamati Coat'' || Jaggu || ||<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/happy-birthday-irrfan-khan-5013880/ |title=Happy birthday Irrfan: The actor whose skills escape definition |publisher=[[The Indian Express]]}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1994 || ''[[The Cloud Door]]'' ||  Irfan ||\n|-\n| ''Purush'' ||  || ||\n|-\n| 1998 || ''[[Bada Din]]'' ||  Police Inspector || ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2000 || ''[[The Goal (film)|The Goal]]'' (Hindi) ||  Anupam Singh ||\n|-\n|| ''[[Ghaath]]'' || Mamu / Romesh Bhagwat Dogra || ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2001|| ''[[The Warrior (2001 British film)|The Warrior]]'' || Lafcadia \u2013 Warrior ||  ||\n|-\n| ''[[Kasoor]]'' || Public Prosecutor Nitin Mehta || ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"| 2002\n| ''Bokshu, The Myth'' || High priest (Tantric yogi) || Indian English film\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2006/film/markets-festivals/bokshu-the-myth-1200515561/|title=Bokshu, The Myth|last=Young|first=Deborah|date=13 June 2006|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=18 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2002/may/22sen.htm|title=Why can't an Indian make a film in English?|last=Warrier|first=Shobha|date=22 May 2002|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=18 December 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Pratha'' || Priest Ninni Pandey || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Kali Salwar]]'' || Shankar || ||<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/movies/unshackling-sultana/article18437382.ece |title=Unshackling Sultana |publisher=[[The Hindu]]}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Gunaah (2002 film)|Gunaah]]'' || Digvijay Pandey || ||\n|-\n| ''Haathi ka Anda''|| Badruddin || ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"| 2003 || ''[[Haasil]]'' || Ranvijay Singh || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Dhund (2003 film)|Dhund: The fog]]'' || Ajit Khurana || || \n|-\n| ''[[Footpath (2003 film)|Footpath]]'' || Sheikh || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Maqbool]]'' || Maqbool || ||\n|-\n| ''[[The Bypass (2003)|The Bypass]]'' || Policeman || || \n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"| 2004 || ''[[Shadows of Time]]'' || Yani Mishra ||  ||\n|-\n| ''[[Aan: Men at Work]]'' || Yusuf Pathan || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Ashvin Kumar|Road to Ladakh]]'' || Terrorist || Short Film ||\n|-\n| ''[[Charas: A Joint Operation]]'' || Ranbhir Singh Rathore || ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"| 2005 || ''[[Chocolate: Deep Dark Secrets|Chocolate]]'' || Pipi || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Rog]]'' || Inspector Uday Rathore || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Chehraa]]'' || Chandranath Diwan || ||\n|-\n| ''[[7\u00bd Phere]]'' || Manoj || ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"| 2006 || ''[[Yun Hota Toh Kya Hota]]'' || Salim Rajabali || ||\n|-\n| ''[[The Film]]'' || Shamim Bhai || Voice over ||\n|-\n| ''[[The Killer (2006 film)|The Killer]]'' || Vikram/Roopchand Swaroopchand Solanki || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Deadline: Sirf 24 Ghante]]'' || Krish Vaidya || ||\n|- \n| ''[[Sainikudu]]'' || Pappu Yadav || [[Telugu cinema|Telugu film]] ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\"| 2007 || ''[[A Mighty Heart (film)|A Mighty Heart]]'' || Zeeshan Kazmi || English movie ||\n|-\n| ''[[Life in a... Metro]]'' || Monty || ||\n|-\n| ''[[The Namesake (film)|The Namesake]]'' || Ashoke Ganguli || English movie ||\n|-\n| ''[[The Darjeeling Limited]]'' || The Father ||  ||\n|-\n| ''[[Apna Asmaan]]'' || Ravi Kumar || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Partition (2007 film)|Partition]]'' || Avtar ||  ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"7\"| 2008 || ''[[Tulsi (film)|Tulsi]]'' || Suraj || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Sunday (2008 film)|Sunday]]'' || Kumar || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Krazzy 4]]'' || Dr. Mukherjee || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Mumbai Meri Jaan]]'' || Thomas || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Slumdog Millionaire]]'' || Police Inspector || English movie ||\n|-\n| ''[[Chamku (film)|Chamku]]'' || Vishal Kapoor || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Dil Kabaddi]]'' || Samit || ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"| 2009 || ''[[Acid Factory]]'' || Kaizar || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Billu]]'' || Billu/Vilas Pardesi || ||\n|-\n| ''[[New York (2009 film)|New York]]'' || Roshan (FBI Official) || ||\n|-\n| ''[[New York, I Love You]]'' || Mansuhkhbai || || \n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 2010 || ''[[Right Yaaa Wrong]]'' || Vinay Patnaik || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Knock Out (2010 film)|Knock Out]]'' || Bacchoo / Tony Khosla || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Hisss]]'' || Inspector Vikram Gupta || ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 2011 || ''[[Yeh Saali Zindagi]]'' || Arun || ||\n|-\n| ''[[7 Khoon Maaf]]'' || Wasiullah Khan a.k.a. Musafir || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Thank You (2011 film)|Thank You]]'' || Vikram || ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 2012 || ''[[Paan Singh Tomar (film)|Paan Singh Tomar]]'' || [[Paan Singh Tomar]] || ||\n|-\n| ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man (2012 film)|The Amazing Spider-Man]]'' || Dr. Rajit Ratha || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Life of Pi (film)|Life of Pi]]'' || Adult Piscine Molitor Patel (\"Pi\") || English movie ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 2013 || ''[[Saheb, Biwi Aur Gangster Returns]]'' || Indrajeet Singh || ||\n|-\n| ''[[D-Day (2013 film)|D-Day]]'' || Wali Khan || ||\n|-\n| ''[[The Lunchbox]]'' || Saajan Fernandes || ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2014 || ''[[Gunday]]'' || A.C.P. Satyajeet Sarkar || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Haider (film)|Haider]]'' || Roohdaar || ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"| 2015 || ''[[Qissa (film)|Qissa]]'' || Umber Singh || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Piku]]'' || Rana Chaudhary || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Jurassic World]]'' || Simon Masrani || English movie ||\n|-\n| ''[[Talvar (film)|Talvar]]'' || Ashwin Kumar || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Jazbaa]]'' || Youhan || ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 2016 || ''[[The Jungle Book (2016 film)|The Jungle Book]]'' || [[Baloo]] (voice) || Hindi dub ||\n|-\n| ''[[Inferno (2016 film)|Inferno]]'' || Harry \"The Provost\" Sims || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Madaari]]'' || Nirmal Kumar || ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"| 2017 || ''[[Hindi Medium (film)|Hindi Medium]]''  || Raj Batra || || \n|-\n| ''[[Doob: No Bed of Roses]]'' || Javed Hasan || [[Indo-Bangla joint production|Bangladesh-India]] joint venture film || \n|-\n| ''[[The Song of Scorpions]]'' || Aadam || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Qarib Qarib Singlle]]'' || Yogi || ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 2018 || ''[[Blackmail (2018 film)|Blackmail]]'' || Dev Kaushal || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Puzzle (2018 film)|Puzzle]]'' || Robert ||English movie \n|\n|-\n| ''[[Karwaan (film)|Karwaan]]'' || Shaukat || ||\n|-\n| 2020 || ''[[Angrezi Medium]]'' || Champak Bansal || ||<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/taran_adarsh/status/1114009094547841024|title=Irrfan Khan resumes work... #AngreziMedium shooting begins in #Udaipur today [5 April 2019]... Directed by Homi Adajania... Produced by Dinesh Vijan... Will be shot in #Udaipur and #London... #AngreziMedium is the sequel to the smash hit #HindiMedium, but with a new story.|last=adarsh|first=taran|publisher=|accessdate=5 April 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Television==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Year !! Show !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n|1985-1986\n|''[[Shrikant (TV show)|Shrikant]]''\n|\n|\n|-\n|1988\n|''[[Bharat Ek Khoj]]''\n|[[Abd al-Qadir Bada'uni]]\n|episode 32 and 33.\n|-\n|1991\n|[[Kahkashan]]\n|\n|\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[Chanakya (TV series)|Chanakya]]''\n|\"Senapati\" Bhadrashal\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1993\n|''Shesh Prashn''\n|Shivnaath\n|\n|-\n|[[kirdaar]]\n|\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1994\n|''[[Chandrakanta (TV series)|Chandrakanta]]''\n|\"Badrinath/Somnath\"\n|\n|-\n|''[[The Great Maratha]]''\n|[[Najib-ud-daula]] and Gulam Kadir Khan\n|\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Banegi Apni Baat]]''\n| Kumar\n|\n|-\n|1995- 1996\n|''Darr''\n|Serial Killer\n|\n|-\n| 1996\n|''[[Just Mohabbat]]''\n|\"Mr. Singh\" \n| episode 4 and 5<ref>{{cite web|title=Just Mohabbat: Episode 4, from SET India official Youtube channel|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=luj495o6X0o}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1997\n|''[[Jai Hanuman]]''\n|[[Maharishi Valmiki]]\n|\n|-\n|''Bombay Blue''\n| Rameez\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|Sparsh\n|\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Star Bestsellers]]''\n|\n| episode \"Ek Shaam Ke Mulaqaat\"\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[Ssshhhh...Koi Hai]]''\n| Amar\n| Episode 9 (Mumkin)<ref>{{cite web|title=Ssshhhh...Koi Hai: Episode 9, from HOTSTAR Official Website|url=https://www.hotstar.com/tv/ssshhhhkoi-hai/s-2097/from-reel-to-real/1000234010}}</ref>\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Kyaa Kahein]]''\n|Host\n|\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[Mano Ya Na Mano (2006 TV series)|Mano Ya Na Mano]]''\n|Host\n|\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[Don (TV series)|Don]]''\n|Host\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[MTV Roadies 7.0|MTV Hero Honda Roadies 7]]''\n|Himself\n|\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[In Treatment (U.S. TV series)|In Treatment]]''\n|Sunil\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Tokyo Trial (miniseries)|Tokyo Trial]]''\n|[[Radhabinod Pal]]\n|\n|}\n\n==Video games==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Show !! Voice role !! Notes\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Lego Jurassic World]]''\n| Simon Masrani \n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Lego Dimensions]]''\n| Simon Masrani \n|\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khan, Irrfan}}\n[[Category:Indian filmographies]]\n[[Category:Actor filmographies]]\n[[Category:Male actor filmographies]]\n", "name_user": "Editor5454", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTelevision", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irrfan_Khan_filmography"}
{"title_page": "Zimmermann Telegram", "text_new": "{{short description|1917 WWI telegram from Germany to Mexico proposing an alliance}}\n[[File:Zimmermann Telegram as Received by the German Ambassador to Mexico - NARA - 302025.jpg|thumb|The Zimmermann Telegram as it was sent from [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]] to Ambassador [[Heinrich von Eckardt]] (who was the German ambassador to [[Mexico]])]]\n[[File:Zimmermann Telegram.svg|thumb|[[Mexico|Mexican]] territory in 1916 (dark green), territory promised to Mexico in the Zimmermann telegram (light green), the pre-1836 original Mexican territory (red line)]]{{Campaignbox Battles of the Mexican Revolution involving the United States}}\n\nThe '''Zimmermann Telegram''' (or '''Zimmermann Note''' or '''Zimmerman Fart''') was a secret diplomatic communication issued from the [[Federal Foreign Office|German Foreign Office]] in January 1917 that proposed a military alliance between [[German Empire|Germany]] and [[Mexico]]. If the [[United States]] entered [[World War I]] against Germany, Mexico would recover [[Texas]], [[Arizona]], and [[New Mexico]]. The telegram was intercepted and decoded by [[Room 40|British intelligence]].\n\nRevelation of the contents fattened Americans, especially after German Foreign Secretary [[Arthur Zimmermann]] publicly admitted on March 3 that the telegram was genuine, helping to generate support for the [[American entry into World War I|United States' declaration of war on Germany]] in April.<ref>*{{cite book |ref= Andrew |last= Andrew |first= Christopher |title= For The President's Eyes Only |year= 1996 |publisher= Harper Collins |isbn= 0-00-638071-9 | page = 42}}</ref> The decryption was described as the most significant intelligence triumph for Britain during World War I,<ref name=BBC2017/> and one of the earliest occasions on which a piece of [[signal intelligence]] influenced world events.<ref name=BBCHistory2017>{{cite news|title=The telegram that brought America into the First World War|url=http://www.historyextra.com/article/bbc-history-magazine/telegram-brought-america-first-world-war|accessdate=17 January 2017|work=BBC History Magazine|date=17 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Telegram content==\n[[File:Arthur Zimmermann.png|thumb|Arthur Zimmermann]]\nThe message came in the form of a [[code (cryptography)|coded]] telegram dispatched by [[Arthur Zimmermann]], a [[Secretary of state#Germany|''Staatssekret\u00e4r'']] (a top-level [[civil servant]]) in the Foreign Office of the German Empire on 19 January 1917. The message was sent to the German ambassador to Mexico, [[Heinrich von Eckardt]].<ref>{{cite news | author = <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->| title = Washington Exposes Plot| url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1917/03/01/102318118.pdf| work = The Associated Press| location = Washington| date = 28 February 1917| access-date  = 11 January 2020}} </ref> Zimmermann sent the telegram in anticipation of the resumption of [[unrestricted submarine warfare]] by Germany on 1 February, which the German government presumed would almost certainly lead to war with the United States. The telegram instructed Eckardt that if the United States appeared certain to enter the war, he was to approach the Mexican Government with a proposal for military alliance with funding from Germany. \n\nThe decoded telegram is as follows:\n\n{{quote|We intend to begin on the first of February unrestricted submarine warfare. We shall endeavor in spite of this to keep the United States of America neutral. In the event of this not succeeding, we make Mexico a proposal of alliance on the following basis: make war together, make peace together, generous financial support and an understanding on our part that Mexico is to reconquer the lost territory in Texas, New Mexico, and Arizona. The settlement in detail is left to you. You will inform the President of the above most secretly as soon as the outbreak of war with the United States of America is certain, and add the suggestion that he should, on his own initiative, invite Japan to immediate adherence and at the same time mediate between Japan and ourselves. Please call the President's attention to the fact that the ruthless employment of our submarines now offers the prospect of compelling England in a few months to make peace.<br>Signed, ZIMMERMANN}}\n\n==Background==\n===Previous German efforts to promote war===\nGermany had long sought to incite a war between Mexico and the United States, which would have tied down American forces and slowed the export of American arms to the [[Allies of World War I|Allies]].<ref>{{cite book |ref= Katz |last= Katz |first= Friedrich |title= The Secret War in Mexico: Europe, the United States, and the Mexican Revolution |year= 1981 |location= |publisher= |isbn= | pages = 328\u2013329}}</ref> The Germans had engaged in a pattern of actively arming, funding, and advising the Mexicans, as shown by the 1914 [[Ypiranga Incident]]<ref>Katz (1981), pp. 232\u2013240.</ref> and the presence of German advisors during the 1918 [[Battle of Ambos Nogales]]. German Naval Intelligence officer [[Franz von Rintelen]] had attempted to incite a war between Mexico and the United States in 1915, giving [[Victoriano Huerta]] $12 million for that purpose.<ref>Katz (1981), pp. 329\u2013332.</ref> The German saboteur [[Lothar Witzke]], responsible for the March 1917 munitions explosion at the [[Mare Island Naval Shipyard]] in the San Francisco Bay Area,<ref>{{cite book |ref= Tucker |first1= Spencer |last1= Tucker |first2= Priscilla Mary |last2= Roberts |title= World War One |location= Santa Barbara CA |publisher= ABC-CLIO |year= 2005 |isbn= 1-85109-420-2 |lastauthoramp= y | page = 1606}}</ref> and possibly responsible for the July 1916 [[Black Tom explosion]] in New Jersey, was based in Mexico City. The failure of United States troops [[Pancho Villa Expedition|to capture Pancho Villa in 1916]] and the movement of President Carranza in favor of Germany emboldened the Germans to send the Zimmermann note.<ref>Katz (1981), pp. 346\u2013347.</ref>\n\nThe German provocations were partially successful. President Woodrow Wilson ordered the [[United States occupation of Veracruz|military invasion of Veracruz]] in 1914 in the context of the Ypiranga Incident and against the advice of the British government.<ref name=\"Michael Small\">{{cite book | first = Michael | last = Small | year = 2009 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=KFgNYgx2rpEC&q=%22anti-american+riots%22#v=onepage&q=%22anti-american%20riots%22&f=false | title = The Forgotten Peace: Mediation at Niagara Falls, 1914 | page = 35 | publisher = University of Ottawa | location = Ottawa, Canada| isbn = 9780776607122 }}</ref> War was prevented thanks to the [[Niagara Falls peace conference]] organized by the [[ABC nations]], but the occupation was a decisive factor in [[Mexico in World War I|Mexican neutrality in World War I]].<ref name=\"Lee Stacy\"/> Mexico refused to participate in the embargo against Germany and granted full guarantees to the German companies for keeping their operations open, specifically in Mexico City.<ref name=\"J\u00fcrgen Buchenau\"/> These guarantees lasted for 25 years; coincidentally, it was on 22 May 1942 that Mexico declared war on the [[Axis Powers]] after the loss of two Mexican-flagged tankers that month to ''[[Kriegsmarine]]'' U-boats.\n\n===German motivation for the telegram===\nThe Zimmermann Telegram was part of an effort carried out by the Germans to postpone the transportation of supplies and other war materials from the United States to the Allied Powers that were at war with Germany.<ref>{{cite book |ref= Tuchman |author-link= Barbara Tuchman |last= Tuchman |first= Barbara W. |title= The Zimmermann Telegram |year= 1958 |isbn= 0-345-32425-0 |pages= [https://archive.org/details/zimmermanntelegr00barb_0/page/63 63, 73\u201374] |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/zimmermanntelegr00barb_0/page/63 }}</ref> The main purpose of the telegram was to make the Mexican government declare war on the United States in hopes of tying down American forces and slowing the export of American arms.<ref>Katz (1981), pp. 328\u2013329.</ref> The [[Oberste Heeresleitung|German High Command]] believed they would be able to defeat the British and French on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] and strangle Britain with unrestricted submarine warfare before American forces could be trained and shipped to Europe in sufficient numbers to aid the Allied Powers. The Germans were encouraged by their successes on the [[Eastern Front (World War I)|Eastern Front]] into believing that they would be able to divert large numbers of troops to the Western Front in support of their goals. The Mexicans were willing to consider the alliance but declined the deal after Americans were informed of the Telegram.\n\n==Mexican response==\nMexican President [[Venustiano Carranza]] assigned a military commission to assess the feasibility of the Mexican takeover of their former territories contemplated by Germany.<ref>Katz (1981), p. 364.</ref> The generals concluded that it would be neither possible nor even desirable to attempt such an enterprise for the following reasons:\n\n* Mexico was in the midst of a civil war, and Carranza's position was far from secure. A declaration of war by his regime would have provided an opportunity for opposing factions to align with the United States and Allied Powers in exchange for diplomatic recognition. \n* The United States was far stronger militarily than Mexico was. Even if Mexico's military forces were completely united and loyal to a single regime, no serious scenario existed under which they could invade and win a war against the United States.\n* Germany's promises of \"generous financial support\" were very unreliable. The German government had already informed Carranza in June 1916 that they were unable to provide the necessary gold needed to stock a completely independent Mexican national bank.<ref name=\"William Beezley\">{{cite book | first1 = William | last1 = Beezley | first2 = Michael | last2 = Meyer | year = 2010 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=Amt1ZXMeVYMC&q=%22gold+to+stock%22#v=snippet&q=%22gold%20to%20stock%22&f=false | title = The Oxford History of Mexico | page = 476 | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = UK| isbn = 9780199779932 }}</ref> Even if Mexico received financial support, it would still need to purchase arms, ammunition, and other needed war supplies from the [[ABC nations]] (Argentina, Brazil, and Chile), which would strain relations with them, as explained below.\n* Even if by some chance Mexico had the military means to win a conflict against the United States and reclaim the territories in question, Mexico would have severe difficulty conquering and pacifying a large English-speaking population that was both used to self-government and [[Second Amendment to the United States Constitution|better supplied with arms]] than most other civilian populations.\n* Other foreign relations were at stake. The ABC nations organized the [[Niagara Falls peace conference]] in 1914 to avoid a full-scale war between the United States and Mexico over the [[United States occupation of Veracruz]]. If Mexico were to enter war against the United States, it would strain relations with those nations.\n\nThe Carranza government was recognized ''[[de jure]]'' by the United States on 31 August 1917 as a direct consequence of the Zimmermann telegram since recognition was necessary to ensure [[Mexico in World War I|Mexican neutrality in World War I]].<ref name=\"Thomas Paterson\">{{cite book | first1 = Thomas | last1 = Paterson | first2 = J. Garry | last2 = Clifford | first3 = Robert | last3 = Brigham | first4 = Michael | last4 = Donoghue | first5 = Kenneth | last5 = Hagan | year = 2010 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=XkfAAgAAQBAJ&q=%22mexican+neutrality%22#v=snippet&q=%22mexican%20neutrality%22&f=false | title = American Foreign Relations, Volume 1: To 1920 | page = 265 | publisher = Cengage Learning | location = USA| isbn = 9781305172104 }}</ref><ref name=\"Paterson Clifford\">{{cite book | first1 = Thomas | last1 = Paterson | first2 = John Garry | last2 = Clifford | first3 = Kenneth J. | last3 = Hagan | year = 1999 | url = https://books.google.com/?id=4TyZFqJjLMAC&q=%22mexican+neutrality%22 | title = American Foreign Relations: A History Since 1895 | page = 51 | publisher = Houghton Mifflin College Division | location = USA| isbn = 9780395938874 }}</ref> After the [[United States occupation of Veracruz|military invasion of Veracruz]] in 1914, Mexico did not participate in any military excursions with the United States in World War I,<ref name=\"Lee Stacy\">{{cite book | first = Lee | last = Stacy | year = 2002 | url = https://books.google.com/?id=84krAQAAMAAJ&q=%22mexican+neutrality%22 | title = Mexico and the United States, Volume 3 | page = 869 | publisher = Marshall Cavendish | location = USA| isbn = 9780761474050 }}</ref> thus ensuring that Mexican neutrality was the best outcome that the United States could hope for, even if Mexican neutrality allowed German companies to keep their operations in Mexico open.<ref name=\"J\u00fcrgen Buchenau\">{{cite book | first = J\u00fcrgen | last = Buchenau | year = 2004 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=zj47Ky6ciJEC&q=%22mexican+neutrality%22#v=snippet&q=%22mexican%20neutrality%22&f=false | title = Tools of Progress: A German Merchant Family in Mexico City, 1865\u2013Present | page = 82 | publisher = University of New Mexico Press | location = USA| isbn = 9780826330888 }}</ref>\n\n==British interception==\n[[File:Ztel2.jpg|thumb|left|A portion of the Telegram as decrypted by [[British Naval Intelligence]] codebreakers. The word ''Arizona'' was not in the German codebook and thus had to be split into phonetic syllables.]]\n\nZimmermann's office sent the telegram to the German embassy in the United States for re-transmission to Eckardt in Mexico. It has traditionally been claimed that the telegram was sent over three routes: transmitted by radio and also sent over two [[transatlantic telegraph cable| trans-Atlantic telegraph cables]] operated by neutral governments (the United States and Sweden) for the use of their diplomatic services, but it has been established that only one method was used. The Germans delivered the message to the [[Embassy of the United States, Berlin|United States embassy in Berlin]], and it then passed by [[diplomatic cable]] first to Copenhagen and then to London for onward transmission over transatlantic cable to Washington.<ref name=\"Gannon\">{{cite book | ref= Gannon | last= Gannon | first= Paul | title= Inside Room 40: The Codebreakers of World War I | location= London | publisher= Ian Allan Publishing | year= 2011 |isbn= 978-0-7110-3408-2}}</ref> [[William Reginald Hall]], the head of [[Room 40]], spread the misinformation about the \"three routes\" to try to conceal from the United States the fact that [[Room 40]] was intercepting its cable traffic.{{citation needed|date= May 2018}}\n\nDirect telegraph transmission of the telegram was impossible because the British had cut the German international cables at the outbreak of war. However, the United States allowed limited use of its diplomatic cables with Germany to communicate with its ambassador in Washington. The facility was supposed to be used for cables connected with President Woodrow Wilson's peace proposals.<ref name=\"Gannon\"/>\n\nThe Swedish cable ran from Sweden, and the United States cable from the United States embassy in [[Denmark]]. However, neither cable ran directly to the United States. Both cables passed through a relay station at [[Porthcurno]], near [[Land's End]], the westernmost tip of England. Here the signals were boosted for the long trans-oceanic jump. All traffic through the Porthcurno relay was copied to British intelligence, particularly to the [[cryptanalysis| codebreakers]] and analysts in [[Room 40]] at the [[Admiralty]].<ref name=\"SigSec\">{{cite book | author-link= Rupert Allason | last= West | first= Nigel | title= The Sigint Secrets: The Signals Intelligence War, 1990 to Today-Including the Persecution of Gordon Welchman | publisher= Quill | location= New York | year= 1990 | isbn= 0-688-09515-1 | pages = 83, 87\u201392}}</ref>\n\nAfter their telegraph cables had been cut, the German Foreign Office appealed to the United States for use of their cable for diplomatic messages. President Wilson agreed in the belief both that such co-operation would sustain continued good relations with Germany and that more efficient German-American diplomacy could assist Wilson's goal of a negotiated end to the war. The Germans handed in messages to the United States embassy in Berlin, which were relayed to the embassy in Denmark and then to the United States by American telegraph operators. However, the United States placed conditions on German usage, most notably that all messages had to be in clear, or uncoded. The Germans assumed that the cable was secure and used it extensively.<ref name=\"SigSec\"/>\n\nHowever, that put German diplomats in a precarious situation: they relied on the United States to transmit Zimmermann's note to its final destination, but the message's unencrypted contents would be deeply alarming to the Americans. The Germans persuaded [[United States Ambassador to Germany |US Ambassador]] [[James W. Gerard]] to accept it in coded form, and it was transmitted on 16 January 1917.<ref name=\"SigSec\"/>\n\nIn Room 40, [[Nigel de Grey]] had partially decoded the telegram by the next day.<ref name=\"Gannon\"/> By 1917, the diplomatic code 13040 had been along for many years\u2009and was old. Since Room 40 had had ample time to reconstruct it cryptanalytically, it was readable to a fair degree. Room 40 had previously obtained German cryptographic documents, including the diplomatic code 3512 (captured in the [[Mesopotamian campaign]]), which was a later, updated code, similar to, but not really related to code 13040, and naval code SKM (Signalbuch der Kaiserlichen Marine),\u2009\u2060useless for decoding the Zimmermann Telegram but valuable when it came to decoding naval traffic, which had been retrieved from the wrecked cruiser [[SMS Magdeburg|SMS ''Magdeburg'']] by the Russians, who passed it to the British.<ref>{{cite book | last1= Polmar | first1= Norman | last2=  Noot | first2= Jurrien | title= Submarines of the Russian and Soviet Navies 1718\u20131990 | location= Annapolis | publisher= US Naval Institute Press | year= 1991 | lastauthoramp= y | ref= Polmar}}</ref> \n\nDisclosure of the telegram would sway public opinion in the United States against Germany if the British could convince the Americans that the text was genuine, but Room 40 chief William Reginald Hall was reluctant to let it out because the disclosure would expose the German codes broken in Room 40 and British eavesdropping on the United States cable. Hall waited three weeks. During this period, de Grey and cryptographer [[William Montgomery (cryptographer) |William Montgomery]] completed the decryption. On 1 February Germany announced resumption of \"unrestricted\" submarine warfare, an act which led the United States to break off diplomatic relations with Germany on 3 February.<ref name=\"SigSec\"/>\n[[File:Zimmermann-telegramm-offen.jpg|thumb|The Telegram, completely decrypted and translated]]\n\nHall passed the telegram to the British Foreign Office on 5 February, but still warned against releasing it. Meanwhile, the British discussed possible cover stories which would serve to explain to the Americans how they obtained the coded text of the telegram without admitting to their ability to intercept American diplomatic communications, which they would continue to do for another 25 years, and also to explain how they obtained the cleartext of the telegram without letting the Germans know that their codes were broken. Furthermore, the British needed to find a way to convince the Americans the message was not a forgery.<ref name=BBC2017>\n{{cite news\n|title= Why was the Zimmerman Telegram so important?\n|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-38581861\n|accessdate= 17 January 2017|work= BBC\n|date= 17 January 2017\n}}\n</ref>\n\nFor the first story, the British obtained the coded text of the telegram from the Mexican commercial telegraph office. The British knew that since the German embassy in Washington would relay the message by commercial telegraph, the Mexican telegraph office would have the coded text. ''\"Mr. H\"'', a British agent in Mexico, bribed an employee of the commercial telegraph company for a copy of the message. (Sir [[Thomas Hohler]], the British ambassador in Mexico, claimed to have been ''\"Mr. H\"'' or at least involved with the interception in his autobiography.{{citation needed|date= May 2018}}) That coded text could be shown to the Americans without embarrassment.\n\nMoreover, the retransmission was encoded with the older code 13040 and so by mid-February, the British had not only the complete text but also the ability to release the telegram without revealing the extent to which the latest German codes had been broken. (At worst, the Germans might have realized that the 13040 code had been compromised, but that was a risk worth taking against the possibility of United States entry into the war.) Finally, since copies of the 13040 codetext would also have been deposited in the records of the American commercial telegraph company, the British had the ability to prove the authenticity of the message to the United States government.<ref name=BBCHistory2017/>\n\nAs a cover story, the British could publicly claim that their agents had stolen the telegram's decoded text in Mexico. Privately, the British needed to give the Americans the 13040 code so that the United States government could verify the authenticity of the message independently with their own commercial telegraphic records, but the Americans agreed to back the official cover story. The German Foreign Office refused to consider a possible code break and instead sent Ambassador Eckardt on a witch-hunt for a traitor in the embassy in Mexico. (Eckardt indignantly rejected the accusations, and the Foreign Office eventually declared the embassy exonerated.)<ref name=\"SigSec\"/>\n\n===Use===\nOn 19 February, Hall showed the telegram to Edward Bell, secretary of the United States Embassy in Britain. Bell, at first incredulous, thought that it was a forgery. Once Bell was convinced the message was genuine, he became enraged. On 20 February, Hall informally sent a copy to United States Ambassador [[Walter Hines Page]]. On 23 February, Page met with British Foreign Minister [[Arthur James Balfour|Arthur Balfour]] and was given the codetext, the message in German, and the English translation. Page then reported the story to President [[Woodrow Wilson]], including details to be verified from telegraph-company files in the United States. Wilson released the text to the media on 28 February 1917.\n\n==American response==\n[[File:Cartoon for a Telegram.jpg|thumb|210px|1917 political cartoon about the Zimmermann Telegram]]\nPopular sentiment in the United States at that time was [[anti-Mexican sentiment|anti-Mexican]] as well as [[anti-German sentiment|anti-German]], and in Mexico there was considerable [[anti-American sentiment]].<ref>{{cite book |ref= Link |last= Link |first= Arthur S. |title= Wilson: Campaigns for Progressivism and Peace: 1916\u20131917 |year= 1965 |url= http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=acls;idno=heb01547.0005.001;rgn=full%20text;view=toc;cc=acls}}</ref> General [[John J. Pershing]] [[Pancho Villa Expedition|had long been chasing]] the revolutionary [[Pancho Villa]] for raiding into US territory  and carried out several cross-border expeditions. News of the telegram further inflamed tensions between the United States and Mexico.\n[[File:Exploding in his Hands.jpg|left|thumb|225x225px|\"Exploding in his Hands\"]]\nHowever, there was also a notable [[anti-British sentiment]] in the United States, particularly among [[German Americans|German-]] and [[Irish American|Irish-Americans]]. Many Americans wished to avoid the conflict in Europe. Since the public had been told falsely that the telegram had been stolen in a decoded form in Mexico, the message was widely believed at first to be an elaborate forgery perpetrated by British intelligence. That belief, which was not restricted to pacifist and pro-German lobbies, was promoted by German and Mexican diplomats and by some American newspapers, especially the [[Hearst Corporation|Hearst]] press empire. That presented the Wilson administration with a dilemma. With the evidence the United States had been provided confidentially by the British, Wilson realized the message was genuine but he could not make the evidence public without compromising the British codebreaking operation.\n\nAny doubts as to the authenticity of the telegram were removed by Zimmermann himself. At a press conference on 3 March 1917, he told an American journalist, \"I cannot deny it. It is true.\" Then, on 29 March 1917, Zimmermann gave a speech in the [[Reichstag (German Empire)|Reichstag]] in which he admitted the telegram was genuine.<ref>{{cite journal |ref= Meyer |last= Meyer |first= Michael C. |title= The Mexican-German Conspiracy of 1915 |journal= The Americas |volume= 23 |issue= 1  |pages= 76\u201389 |year=1966 |doi=10.2307/980141|jstor= 980141 }}</ref> Zimmermann hoped that Americans would understand that the idea was that Germany would only fund Mexico's war with the United States in the prior event of American entry into World War I.\n\nOn 1 February 1917, Germany began unrestricted submarine warfare against all ships in the Atlantic bearing the American flag, both passenger and merchant ships.  Two ships were sunk in February, and most American shipping companies held their ships in port. Besides the highly provocative war proposal to Mexico, the telegram also mentioned \"ruthless employment of our submarines\". Public opinion demanded action. Wilson had previously refused to assign US Navy crews and guns to the merchant ships. However, once the Zimmermann note was public, Wilson called for arming the merchant ships, but [[anti-war]] elements in the [[United States Senate]] blocked his proposal.<ref>{{cite book | first = Richard W | last = Leopold | title = The Growth of American Foreign Policy: A History | year = 1962 | pages = 330\u201331 | publisher = Random House}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April 1917, Congress voted to [[United States declaration of war on Germany (1917)|declare war on Germany]]; Wilson had asked [[United States Congress|Congress]] for \"a [[The war to end war|war to end all wars]]\" that would \"make the world safe for democracy\".<ref>{{cite book |first=Arthur S. |last=Link |title=Woodrow Wilson and the Progressive Era, 1910\u20131917 |year=1972 |location=New York |publisher=Harper & Row |pages=252\u2013282 |isbn= }}</ref>\n\nWoodrow Wilson considered another military invasion of Veracruz and [[Tampico]] in 1917\u20131918,<ref name=\"Ernest Gruening\">{{cite book | first = Ernest | last = Gruening | year = 1968 | url = https://books.google.com/?id=VoBlAAAAMAAJ&q=occupation+president+wilson | title = Mexico and Its Heritage | page = 596 | publisher = Greenwood Press | location = U.S.}}</ref><ref name=\"Halevy\">{{cite book | first = Drew Philip | last = Halevy | year = 2000 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=WOfKxFigGSwC | title = Threats of Intervention: U. S.-Mexican Relations, 1917\u20131923 | page = 41 | publisher = iUniverse | location = U.S.| isbn = 9781469701783 }}</ref> so as to pacify the [[Isthmus of Tehuantepec|Tehuantepec Isthmus]] and Tampico oil fields and ensure their continued production during the civil war,<ref name=\"Halevy\" /><ref name=\"MeyerL-p45\">{{cite book | first = Lorenzo | last = Meyer | year = 1977 | url = https://books.google.com/?id=PAy1AAAAIAAJ&q=lansing+tehuantepec | title = Mexico and the United States in the Oil Controversy, 1917\u20131942 | page = 45 | publisher = University of Texas Press | location = U.S.| isbn = 9780292750326 }}</ref> but this time the relatively new Mexican President [[Venustiano Carranza]] threatened to destroy the oil fields in the event that the Marines landed there.<ref name=\"Stephen Haber\">{{cite book | first1 = Stephen | last1 = Haber | first2 = Noel | last2 = Maurer | first3 = Armando | last3 = Razo | year = 2003 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=znZ8Y8lO7_4C&q=+%22burning+of+the+oil+fields%22#v=snippet&q=%22burning%20of%20the%20oil%20fields%22&f=false | title = The Politics of Property Rights: Political Instability, Credible Commitments, and Economic Growth in Mexico, 1876\u20131929 | page = 201 | publisher = Cambridge University Press | location = UK| isbn = 9780521820677 }}</ref><ref name=\"MeyerL-p44\">Meyer, Lorenzo (1977), [https://books.google.com/books?id=PAy1AAAAIAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=destroy+fields p. 44]</ref>\n\n==Japanese response==\nThe government of Japan, another nation mentioned in the Zimmerman Telegram, was already involved in World War I, on the side of the Allied Powers against Germany. The Japanese government later released a statement that Japan was not interested in changing sides and attacking America.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://historyguy.com/zimmerman_telegram.htm | title = Zimmerman Telegram: What Was The Zimmerman Telegram, and How Did It Affect World War One? | date = | first = Roger | last = Lee | work = The History Guy | access-date = 27 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Autograph discovery==\nIn October 2005, it was reported that an original typescript of the decoded Zimmermann Telegram had recently been discovered by an unnamed historian who was researching and preparing an official history of the United Kingdom's [[Government Communications Headquarters]] (GCHQ). The document is believed to be the actual telegram shown to the American ambassador in London in 1917. Marked in Admiral Hall's handwriting at the top of the document are the words: \"This is the one handed to Dr Page and exposed by the President.\" Since many of the secret documents in this incident had been destroyed, it had previously been assumed that the original typed \"decrypt\" was gone forever. However, after the discovery of this document, the GCHQ official historian said: \"I believe that this is indeed the same document that Balfour handed to Page.\"<ref>{{cite news |ref= Fenton |last= Fenton |first= Ben |work= The Telegraph |location= London |date= 17 October 2005 |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1500812/Telegram-that-brought-US-into-Great-War-is-found-found.html  |title= Telegram that brought US into Great War is Found Found }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Germany|Mexico|World War I|United States}}\n*[[American entry into World War I]]\n*[[Imperial German plans for the invasion of the United States]]\n*[[Mexico in World War I]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{Moreinline|section|date=July 2018}}\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |ref= Beesly|last= Beesly |first= Patrick |author-link=Patrick Beesly |year= 1982 |title= Room 40: British Naval Intelligence, 1914\u20131918 |location= New York |publisher= Harcourt, Brace, Jovanovich |isbn= 0-15-178634-8}}\n*{{cite book |ref= Boghardt |last= Boghardt |first= Thomas |author-link= Thomas Boghardt|date= November 2003 |title= The Zimmermann Telegram: Diplomacy, Intelligence and The American Entry into World War I |series= Working Paper Series |url= http://cges.georgetown.edu/docs/docs_working_papers_page/working_paper_boghardt_6-04.pdf |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060902235946/http://cges.georgetown.edu/docs/Docs_Working_Papers_Page/Working_Paper_Boghardt_6-04.pdf |archivedate= September 2, 2006 |publisher= The BMW Center for German and European Studies, [[Edmund A. Walsh School of Foreign Service]], [[Georgetown University]] |location= Washington DC |id= 6-04}}; 35pp\n* {{cite book | last = Boghardt | first = Thomas | title = The Zimmermann Telegram: Intelligence, Diplomacy, and America's Entry into World War I | year = 2012 | page = 319| isbn = 978-1612511481 }}\n* {{cite book |ref= Capozzola |last=Capozzola |first=Christopher |date= 2008 |title=Uncle Sam Wants You: World War I and the Making of the Modern American Citizen |location=Oxford |publisher=Oxford Scholarship Online |isbn=9780195335491|url=http://www.oxfordscholarship.com/view/10.1093/acprof:oso/9780195335491.001.0001/acprof-9780195335491}}\n*{{cite book |ref= Hopkirk |author-link= Peter Hopkirk |last= Hopkirk |first= Peter |year= 1994 |title= On Secret Service East of Constantinople |location= Oxford |publisher= [[Oxford University Press]] |isbn= 0-19-280230-5}}\n*{{cite book |ref= Massie |author-link= Robert Massie |last= Massie |first= Robert K.  |title= [[Castles of Steel]] |publisher= Vintage Books |location= London |year= 2007 |isbn= 978-0-09-952378-9}}\n*{{cite book |ref= Pommerin |last= Pommerin |first= Reiner |year= 1996 |chapter= Reichstagsrede Zimmermanns (Auszug), 30. M\u00e4rz 1917 |title= 'Quellen zu den deutsch-amerikanischen Beziehungen |location= Darmstadt |publisher= Wissenschaftliche Buchgesellschaft Vol. 1 |pages= 213\u201316}}\n*{{cite news|ref= Singh |author1=Singh, Simon|authorlink1=Simon Singh|title=The Zimmermann Telegraph|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/historical-notes-184-kings-road-tighnabruaich-1117153.html|accessdate=14 August 2014|work=The Independent|publisher=Independent Print Limited|date=8 September 1999|archiveurl=http://simonsingh.net/media/articles/maths-and-science/the-zimmermann-telegram/|archivedate=1999}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |ref= Bernstorff |last= Bernstorff |first= Count Johann Heinrich |year= 1920 |title= My Three Years in America |location= New York |publisher= Scribner |pages= 310\u201311}}\n*{{cite journal | last = Bridges | first = Lamar W. | title = Zimmermann telegram: reaction of Southern, Southwestern newspapers | journal = Journalism & Mass Communication Quarterly | year = 1969 | volume = 46 | issue = 1 | pages = 81\u201386 | doi=10.1177/107769906904600112}}\n*{{cite book |last= Dugdale |first= Blanche |year= 1937 |title= Arthur James Balfour |location= New York |publisher= Putnam |at=  Vol. II, pp.&nbsp;127\u2013129}}\n*{{cite book |last= Hendrick |first= Burton J. |origyear=1925 |year= 2003 |title= The Life and Letters of Walter H. Page |publisher= [[Kessinger Publishing]] |isbn= 0-7661-7106-X}}\n*{{cite book |last= Kahn |first= David  |origyear= 1967 |year= 1996 |title= The Codebreakers |location= New York |publisher= Macmillan}}\n*{{cite book |last= Winkler |first= Jonathan Reed |year= 2008 |title= Nexus: Strategic Communications and American Security in World War I |location= Cambridge, MA |publisher= [[Harvard University Press]] |isbn= 978-0-674-02839-5}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisource|Zimmermann Telegram}}\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://texashistory.unt.edu/young/educators/wwI/index.shtml Failed Diplomacy: the Zimmermann Telegram]\n*[http://www.ourdocuments.gov/doc.php?doc=60 Our Documents \u2013 Zimmermann Telegram (1917)]\n*[http://germannavalwarfare.info/indexMEX.htm GermanNavalWarfare.info], Some Original Documents from the British Admiralty, [[Room 40]], regarding the Zimmermann-/Mexico Telegram: Photocopies from [[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|The National Archives]], Kew, Richmond, UK.\n*[http://www.shorpy.com/node/11156?size=_original Moving out of German Embassy after breaking relations, 1917]\n*[https://cosec.bit.uni-bonn.de/fileadmin/user_upload/publications/pubs/gat07a.pdf Zimmermann Telegram: The Original Document, accessed 21 Feb 2015]\n{{Authority control}}\n{{World War I}}\n[[Category:United States documents]]\n[[Category:History of cryptography]]\n[[Category:Telegrams]]\n[[Category:World War I]]\n[[Category:World War I documents]]\n[[Category:Signals intelligence of World War I]]\n[[Category:History of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Germany\u2013Mexico relations]]\n[[Category:Germany\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:1917 in Mexico]]\n[[Category:1917 in Germany]]\n[[Category:1917 in the United States]]\n[[Category:1917 in international relations]]\n[[Category:Diplomatic incidents]]\n[[Category:1916 documents]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1917 WWI telegram from Germany to Mexico proposing an alliance}}\n[[File:Zimmermann Telegram as Received by the German Ambassador to Mexico - NARA - 302025.jpg|thumb|The Zimmermann Telegram as it was sent from [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]] to Ambassador [[Heinrich von Eckardt]] (who was the German ambassador to [[Mexico]])]]\n[[File:Zimmermann Telegram.svg|thumb|[[Mexico|Mexican]] territory in 1916 (dark green), territory promised to Mexico in the Zimmermann telegram (light green), the pre-1836 original Mexican territory (red line)]]{{Campaignbox Battles of the Mexican Revolution involving the United States}}\n\nThe '''Zimmermann Telegram''' (or '''Zimmermann Note''' or '''Zimmerman Cable''') was a secret diplomatic communication issued from the [[Federal Foreign Office|German Foreign Office]] in January 1917 that proposed a military alliance between [[German Empire|Germany]] and [[Mexico]]. If the [[United States]] entered [[World War I]] against Germany, Mexico would recover [[Texas]], [[Arizona]], and [[New Mexico]]. The telegram was intercepted and decoded by [[Room 40|British intelligence]].\n\nRevelation of the contents enraged Americans, especially after German Foreign Secretary [[Arthur Zimmermann]] publicly admitted on March 3 that the telegram was genuine, helping to generate support for the [[American entry into World War I|United States' declaration of war on Germany]] in April.<ref>*{{cite book |ref= Andrew |last= Andrew |first= Christopher |title= For The President's Eyes Only |year= 1996 |publisher= Harper Collins |isbn= 0-00-638071-9 | page = 42}}</ref> The decryption was described as the most significant intelligence triumph for Britain during World War I,<ref name=BBC2017/> and one of the earliest occasions on which a piece of [[signal intelligence]] influenced world events.<ref name=BBCHistory2017>{{cite news|title=The telegram that brought America into the First World War|url=http://www.historyextra.com/article/bbc-history-magazine/telegram-brought-america-first-world-war|accessdate=17 January 2017|work=BBC History Magazine|date=17 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Telegram content==\n[[File:Arthur Zimmermann.png|thumb|Arthur Zimmermann]]\nThe message came in the form of a [[code (cryptography)|coded]] telegram dispatched by [[Arthur Zimmermann]], a [[Secretary of state#Germany|''Staatssekret\u00e4r'']] (a top-level [[civil servant]]) in the Foreign Office of the German Empire on 19 January 1917. The message was sent to the German ambassador to Mexico, [[Heinrich von Eckardt]].<ref>{{cite news | author = <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->| title = Washington Exposes Plot| url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1917/03/01/102318118.pdf| work = The Associated Press| location = Washington| date = 28 February 1917| access-date  = 11 January 2020}} </ref> Zimmermann sent the telegram in anticipation of the resumption of [[unrestricted submarine warfare]] by Germany on 1 February, which the German government presumed would almost certainly lead to war with the United States. The telegram instructed Eckardt that if the United States appeared certain to enter the war, he was to approach the Mexican Government with a proposal for military alliance with funding from Germany. \n\nThe decoded telegram is as follows:\n\n{{quote|We intend to begin on the first of February unrestricted submarine warfare. We shall endeavor in spite of this to keep the United States of America neutral. In the event of this not succeeding, we make Mexico a proposal of alliance on the following basis: make war together, make peace together, generous financial support and an understanding on our part that Mexico is to reconquer the lost territory in Texas, New Mexico, and Arizona. The settlement in detail is left to you. You will inform the President of the above most secretly as soon as the outbreak of war with the United States of America is certain, and add the suggestion that he should, on his own initiative, invite Japan to immediate adherence and at the same time mediate between Japan and ourselves. Please call the President's attention to the fact that the ruthless employment of our submarines now offers the prospect of compelling England in a few months to make peace.<br>Signed, ZIMMERMANN}}\n\n==Background==\n===Previous German efforts to promote war===\nGermany had long sought to incite a war between Mexico and the United States, which would have tied down American forces and slowed the export of American arms to the [[Allies of World War I|Allies]].<ref>{{cite book |ref= Katz |last= Katz |first= Friedrich |title= The Secret War in Mexico: Europe, the United States, and the Mexican Revolution |year= 1981 |location= |publisher= |isbn= | pages = 328\u2013329}}</ref> The Germans had engaged in a pattern of actively arming, funding, and advising the Mexicans, as shown by the 1914 [[Ypiranga Incident]]<ref>Katz (1981), pp. 232\u2013240.</ref> and the presence of German advisors during the 1918 [[Battle of Ambos Nogales]]. German Naval Intelligence officer [[Franz von Rintelen]] had attempted to incite a war between Mexico and the United States in 1915, giving [[Victoriano Huerta]] $12 million for that purpose.<ref>Katz (1981), pp. 329\u2013332.</ref> The German saboteur [[Lothar Witzke]], responsible for the March 1917 munitions explosion at the [[Mare Island Naval Shipyard]] in the San Francisco Bay Area,<ref>{{cite book |ref= Tucker |first1= Spencer |last1= Tucker |first2= Priscilla Mary |last2= Roberts |title= World War One |location= Santa Barbara CA |publisher= ABC-CLIO |year= 2005 |isbn= 1-85109-420-2 |lastauthoramp= y | page = 1606}}</ref> and possibly responsible for the July 1916 [[Black Tom explosion]] in New Jersey, was based in Mexico City. The failure of United States troops [[Pancho Villa Expedition|to capture Pancho Villa in 1916]] and the movement of President Carranza in favor of Germany emboldened the Germans to send the Zimmermann note.<ref>Katz (1981), pp. 346\u2013347.</ref>\n\nThe German provocations were partially successful. President Woodrow Wilson ordered the [[United States occupation of Veracruz|military invasion of Veracruz]] in 1914 in the context of the Ypiranga Incident and against the advice of the British government.<ref name=\"Michael Small\">{{cite book | first = Michael | last = Small | year = 2009 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=KFgNYgx2rpEC&q=%22anti-american+riots%22#v=onepage&q=%22anti-american%20riots%22&f=false | title = The Forgotten Peace: Mediation at Niagara Falls, 1914 | page = 35 | publisher = University of Ottawa | location = Ottawa, Canada| isbn = 9780776607122 }}</ref> War was prevented thanks to the [[Niagara Falls peace conference]] organized by the [[ABC nations]], but the occupation was a decisive factor in [[Mexico in World War I|Mexican neutrality in World War I]].<ref name=\"Lee Stacy\"/> Mexico refused to participate in the embargo against Germany and granted full guarantees to the German companies for keeping their operations open, specifically in Mexico City.<ref name=\"J\u00fcrgen Buchenau\"/> These guarantees lasted for 25 years; coincidentally, it was on 22 May 1942 that Mexico declared war on the [[Axis Powers]] after the loss of two Mexican-flagged tankers that month to ''[[Kriegsmarine]]'' U-boats.\n\n===German motivation for the telegram===\nThe Zimmermann Telegram was part of an effort carried out by the Germans to postpone the transportation of supplies and other war materials from the United States to the Allied Powers that were at war with Germany.<ref>{{cite book |ref= Tuchman |author-link= Barbara Tuchman |last= Tuchman |first= Barbara W. |title= The Zimmermann Telegram |year= 1958 |isbn= 0-345-32425-0 |pages= [https://archive.org/details/zimmermanntelegr00barb_0/page/63 63, 73\u201374] |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/zimmermanntelegr00barb_0/page/63 }}</ref> The main purpose of the telegram was to make the Mexican government declare war on the United States in hopes of tying down American forces and slowing the export of American arms.<ref>Katz (1981), pp. 328\u2013329.</ref> The [[Oberste Heeresleitung|German High Command]] believed they would be able to defeat the British and French on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] and strangle Britain with unrestricted submarine warfare before American forces could be trained and shipped to Europe in sufficient numbers to aid the Allied Powers. The Germans were encouraged by their successes on the [[Eastern Front (World War I)|Eastern Front]] into believing that they would be able to divert large numbers of troops to the Western Front in support of their goals. The Mexicans were willing to consider the alliance but declined the deal after Americans were informed of the Telegram.\n\n==Mexican response==\nMexican President [[Venustiano Carranza]] assigned a military commission to assess the feasibility of the Mexican takeover of their former territories contemplated by Germany.<ref>Katz (1981), p. 364.</ref> The generals concluded that it would be neither possible nor even desirable to attempt such an enterprise for the following reasons:\n\n* Mexico was in the midst of a civil war, and Carranza's position was far from secure. A declaration of war by his regime would have provided an opportunity for opposing factions to align with the United States and Allied Powers in exchange for diplomatic recognition. \n* The United States was far stronger militarily than Mexico was. Even if Mexico's military forces were completely united and loyal to a single regime, no serious scenario existed under which they could invade and win a war against the United States.\n* Germany's promises of \"generous financial support\" were very unreliable. The German government had already informed Carranza in June 1916 that they were unable to provide the necessary gold needed to stock a completely independent Mexican national bank.<ref name=\"William Beezley\">{{cite book | first1 = William | last1 = Beezley | first2 = Michael | last2 = Meyer | year = 2010 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=Amt1ZXMeVYMC&q=%22gold+to+stock%22#v=snippet&q=%22gold%20to%20stock%22&f=false | title = The Oxford History of Mexico | page = 476 | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = UK| isbn = 9780199779932 }}</ref> Even if Mexico received financial support, it would still need to purchase arms, ammunition, and other needed war supplies from the [[ABC nations]] (Argentina, Brazil, and Chile), which would strain relations with them, as explained below.\n* Even if by some chance Mexico had the military means to win a conflict against the United States and reclaim the territories in question, Mexico would have severe difficulty conquering and pacifying a large English-speaking population that was both used to self-government and [[Second Amendment to the United States Constitution|better supplied with arms]] than most other civilian populations.\n* Other foreign relations were at stake. The ABC nations organized the [[Niagara Falls peace conference]] in 1914 to avoid a full-scale war between the United States and Mexico over the [[United States occupation of Veracruz]]. If Mexico were to enter war against the United States, it would strain relations with those nations.\n\nThe Carranza government was recognized ''[[de jure]]'' by the United States on 31 August 1917 as a direct consequence of the Zimmermann telegram since recognition was necessary to ensure [[Mexico in World War I|Mexican neutrality in World War I]].<ref name=\"Thomas Paterson\">{{cite book | first1 = Thomas | last1 = Paterson | first2 = J. Garry | last2 = Clifford | first3 = Robert | last3 = Brigham | first4 = Michael | last4 = Donoghue | first5 = Kenneth | last5 = Hagan | year = 2010 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=XkfAAgAAQBAJ&q=%22mexican+neutrality%22#v=snippet&q=%22mexican%20neutrality%22&f=false | title = American Foreign Relations, Volume 1: To 1920 | page = 265 | publisher = Cengage Learning | location = USA| isbn = 9781305172104 }}</ref><ref name=\"Paterson Clifford\">{{cite book | first1 = Thomas | last1 = Paterson | first2 = John Garry | last2 = Clifford | first3 = Kenneth J. | last3 = Hagan | year = 1999 | url = https://books.google.com/?id=4TyZFqJjLMAC&q=%22mexican+neutrality%22 | title = American Foreign Relations: A History Since 1895 | page = 51 | publisher = Houghton Mifflin College Division | location = USA| isbn = 9780395938874 }}</ref> After the [[United States occupation of Veracruz|military invasion of Veracruz]] in 1914, Mexico did not participate in any military excursions with the United States in World War I,<ref name=\"Lee Stacy\">{{cite book | first = Lee | last = Stacy | year = 2002 | url = https://books.google.com/?id=84krAQAAMAAJ&q=%22mexican+neutrality%22 | title = Mexico and the United States, Volume 3 | page = 869 | publisher = Marshall Cavendish | location = USA| isbn = 9780761474050 }}</ref> thus ensuring that Mexican neutrality was the best outcome that the United States could hope for, even if Mexican neutrality allowed German companies to keep their operations in Mexico open.<ref name=\"J\u00fcrgen Buchenau\">{{cite book | first = J\u00fcrgen | last = Buchenau | year = 2004 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=zj47Ky6ciJEC&q=%22mexican+neutrality%22#v=snippet&q=%22mexican%20neutrality%22&f=false | title = Tools of Progress: A German Merchant Family in Mexico City, 1865\u2013Present | page = 82 | publisher = University of New Mexico Press | location = USA| isbn = 9780826330888 }}</ref>\n\n==British interception==\n[[File:Ztel2.jpg|thumb|left|A portion of the Telegram as decrypted by [[British Naval Intelligence]] codebreakers. The word ''Arizona'' was not in the German codebook and thus had to be split into phonetic syllables.]]\n\nZimmermann's office sent the telegram to the German embassy in the United States for re-transmission to Eckardt in Mexico. It has traditionally been claimed that the telegram was sent over three routes: transmitted by radio and also sent over two [[transatlantic telegraph cable| trans-Atlantic telegraph cables]] operated by neutral governments (the United States and Sweden) for the use of their diplomatic services, but it has been established that only one method was used. The Germans delivered the message to the [[Embassy of the United States, Berlin|United States embassy in Berlin]], and it then passed by [[diplomatic cable]] first to Copenhagen and then to London for onward transmission over transatlantic cable to Washington.<ref name=\"Gannon\">{{cite book | ref= Gannon | last= Gannon | first= Paul | title= Inside Room 40: The Codebreakers of World War I | location= London | publisher= Ian Allan Publishing | year= 2011 |isbn= 978-0-7110-3408-2}}</ref> [[William Reginald Hall]], the head of [[Room 40]], spread the misinformation about the \"three routes\" to try to conceal from the United States the fact that [[Room 40]] was intercepting its cable traffic.{{citation needed|date= May 2018}}\n\nDirect telegraph transmission of the telegram was impossible because the British had cut the German international cables at the outbreak of war. However, the United States allowed limited use of its diplomatic cables with Germany to communicate with its ambassador in Washington. The facility was supposed to be used for cables connected with President Woodrow Wilson's peace proposals.<ref name=\"Gannon\"/>\n\nThe Swedish cable ran from Sweden, and the United States cable from the United States embassy in [[Denmark]]. However, neither cable ran directly to the United States. Both cables passed through a relay station at [[Porthcurno]], near [[Land's End]], the westernmost tip of England. Here the signals were boosted for the long trans-oceanic jump. All traffic through the Porthcurno relay was copied to British intelligence, particularly to the [[cryptanalysis| codebreakers]] and analysts in [[Room 40]] at the [[Admiralty]].<ref name=\"SigSec\">{{cite book | author-link= Rupert Allason | last= West | first= Nigel | title= The Sigint Secrets: The Signals Intelligence War, 1990 to Today-Including the Persecution of Gordon Welchman | publisher= Quill | location= New York | year= 1990 | isbn= 0-688-09515-1 | pages = 83, 87\u201392}}</ref>\n\nAfter their telegraph cables had been cut, the German Foreign Office appealed to the United States for use of their cable for diplomatic messages. President Wilson agreed in the belief both that such co-operation would sustain continued good relations with Germany and that more efficient German-American diplomacy could assist Wilson's goal of a negotiated end to the war. The Germans handed in messages to the United States embassy in Berlin, which were relayed to the embassy in Denmark and then to the United States by American telegraph operators. However, the United States placed conditions on German usage, most notably that all messages had to be in clear, or uncoded. The Germans assumed that the cable was secure and used it extensively.<ref name=\"SigSec\"/>\n\nHowever, that put German diplomats in a precarious situation: they relied on the United States to transmit Zimmermann's note to its final destination, but the message's unencrypted contents would be deeply alarming to the Americans. The Germans persuaded [[United States Ambassador to Germany |US Ambassador]] [[James W. Gerard]] to accept it in coded form, and it was transmitted on 16 January 1917.<ref name=\"SigSec\"/>\n\nIn Room 40, [[Nigel de Grey]] had partially decoded the telegram by the next day.<ref name=\"Gannon\"/> By 1917, the diplomatic code 13040 had been along for many years\u2009and was old. Since Room 40 had had ample time to reconstruct it cryptanalytically, it was readable to a fair degree. Room 40 had previously obtained German cryptographic documents, including the diplomatic code 3512 (captured in the [[Mesopotamian campaign]]), which was a later, updated code, similar to, but not really related to code 13040, and naval code SKM (Signalbuch der Kaiserlichen Marine),\u2009\u2060useless for decoding the Zimmermann Telegram but valuable when it came to decoding naval traffic, which had been retrieved from the wrecked cruiser [[SMS Magdeburg|SMS ''Magdeburg'']] by the Russians, who passed it to the British.<ref>{{cite book | last1= Polmar | first1= Norman | last2=  Noot | first2= Jurrien | title= Submarines of the Russian and Soviet Navies 1718\u20131990 | location= Annapolis | publisher= US Naval Institute Press | year= 1991 | lastauthoramp= y | ref= Polmar}}</ref> \n\nDisclosure of the telegram would sway public opinion in the United States against Germany if the British could convince the Americans that the text was genuine, but Room 40 chief William Reginald Hall was reluctant to let it out because the disclosure would expose the German codes broken in Room 40 and British eavesdropping on the United States cable. Hall waited three weeks. During this period, de Grey and cryptographer [[William Montgomery (cryptographer) |William Montgomery]] completed the decryption. On 1 February Germany announced resumption of \"unrestricted\" submarine warfare, an act which led the United States to break off diplomatic relations with Germany on 3 February.<ref name=\"SigSec\"/>\n[[File:Zimmermann-telegramm-offen.jpg|thumb|The Telegram, completely decrypted and translated]]\n\nHall passed the telegram to the British Foreign Office on 5 February, but still warned against releasing it. Meanwhile, the British discussed possible cover stories which would serve to explain to the Americans how they obtained the coded text of the telegram without admitting to their ability to intercept American diplomatic communications, which they would continue to do for another 25 years, and also to explain how they obtained the cleartext of the telegram without letting the Germans know that their codes were broken. Furthermore, the British needed to find a way to convince the Americans the message was not a forgery.<ref name=BBC2017>\n{{cite news\n|title= Why was the Zimmerman Telegram so important?\n|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-38581861\n|accessdate= 17 January 2017|work= BBC\n|date= 17 January 2017\n}}\n</ref>\n\nFor the first story, the British obtained the coded text of the telegram from the Mexican commercial telegraph office. The British knew that since the German embassy in Washington would relay the message by commercial telegraph, the Mexican telegraph office would have the coded text. ''\"Mr. H\"'', a British agent in Mexico, bribed an employee of the commercial telegraph company for a copy of the message. (Sir [[Thomas Hohler]], the British ambassador in Mexico, claimed to have been ''\"Mr. H\"'' or at least involved with the interception in his autobiography.{{citation needed|date= May 2018}}) That coded text could be shown to the Americans without embarrassment.\n\nMoreover, the retransmission was encoded with the older code 13040 and so by mid-February, the British had not only the complete text but also the ability to release the telegram without revealing the extent to which the latest German codes had been broken. (At worst, the Germans might have realized that the 13040 code had been compromised, but that was a risk worth taking against the possibility of United States entry into the war.) Finally, since copies of the 13040 codetext would also have been deposited in the records of the American commercial telegraph company, the British had the ability to prove the authenticity of the message to the United States government.<ref name=BBCHistory2017/>\n\nAs a cover story, the British could publicly claim that their agents had stolen the telegram's decoded text in Mexico. Privately, the British needed to give the Americans the 13040 code so that the United States government could verify the authenticity of the message independently with their own commercial telegraphic records, but the Americans agreed to back the official cover story. The German Foreign Office refused to consider a possible code break and instead sent Ambassador Eckardt on a witch-hunt for a traitor in the embassy in Mexico. (Eckardt indignantly rejected the accusations, and the Foreign Office eventually declared the embassy exonerated.)<ref name=\"SigSec\"/>\n\n===Use===\nOn 19 February, Hall showed the telegram to Edward Bell, secretary of the United States Embassy in Britain. Bell, at first incredulous, thought that it was a forgery. Once Bell was convinced the message was genuine, he became enraged. On 20 February, Hall informally sent a copy to United States Ambassador [[Walter Hines Page]]. On 23 February, Page met with British Foreign Minister [[Arthur James Balfour|Arthur Balfour]] and was given the codetext, the message in German, and the English translation. Page then reported the story to President [[Woodrow Wilson]], including details to be verified from telegraph-company files in the United States. Wilson released the text to the media on 28 February 1917.\n\n==American response==\n[[File:Cartoon for a Telegram.jpg|thumb|210px|1917 political cartoon about the Zimmermann Telegram]]\nPopular sentiment in the United States at that time was [[anti-Mexican sentiment|anti-Mexican]] as well as [[anti-German sentiment|anti-German]], and in Mexico there was considerable [[anti-American sentiment]].<ref>{{cite book |ref= Link |last= Link |first= Arthur S. |title= Wilson: Campaigns for Progressivism and Peace: 1916\u20131917 |year= 1965 |url= http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=acls;idno=heb01547.0005.001;rgn=full%20text;view=toc;cc=acls}}</ref> General [[John J. Pershing]] [[Pancho Villa Expedition|had long been chasing]] the revolutionary [[Pancho Villa]] for raiding into US territory  and carried out several cross-border expeditions. News of the telegram further inflamed tensions between the United States and Mexico.\n[[File:Exploding in his Hands.jpg|left|thumb|225x225px|\"Exploding in his Hands\"]]\nHowever, there was also a notable [[anti-British sentiment]] in the United States, particularly among [[German Americans|German-]] and [[Irish American|Irish-Americans]]. Many Americans wished to avoid the conflict in Europe. Since the public had been told falsely that the telegram had been stolen in a decoded form in Mexico, the message was widely believed at first to be an elaborate forgery perpetrated by British intelligence. That belief, which was not restricted to pacifist and pro-German lobbies, was promoted by German and Mexican diplomats and by some American newspapers, especially the [[Hearst Corporation|Hearst]] press empire. That presented the Wilson administration with a dilemma. With the evidence the United States had been provided confidentially by the British, Wilson realized the message was genuine but he could not make the evidence public without compromising the British codebreaking operation.\n\nAny doubts as to the authenticity of the telegram were removed by Zimmermann himself. At a press conference on 3 March 1917, he told an American journalist, \"I cannot deny it. It is true.\" Then, on 29 March 1917, Zimmermann gave a speech in the [[Reichstag (German Empire)|Reichstag]] in which he admitted the telegram was genuine.<ref>{{cite journal |ref= Meyer |last= Meyer |first= Michael C. |title= The Mexican-German Conspiracy of 1915 |journal= The Americas |volume= 23 |issue= 1  |pages= 76\u201389 |year=1966 |doi=10.2307/980141|jstor= 980141 }}</ref> Zimmermann hoped that Americans would understand that the idea was that Germany would only fund Mexico's war with the United States in the prior event of American entry into World War I.\n\nOn 1 February 1917, Germany began unrestricted submarine warfare against all ships in the Atlantic bearing the American flag, both passenger and merchant ships.  Two ships were sunk in February, and most American shipping companies held their ships in port. Besides the highly provocative war proposal to Mexico, the telegram also mentioned \"ruthless employment of our submarines\". Public opinion demanded action. Wilson had previously refused to assign US Navy crews and guns to the merchant ships. However, once the Zimmermann note was public, Wilson called for arming the merchant ships, but [[anti-war]] elements in the [[United States Senate]] blocked his proposal.<ref>{{cite book | first = Richard W | last = Leopold | title = The Growth of American Foreign Policy: A History | year = 1962 | pages = 330\u201331 | publisher = Random House}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April 1917, Congress voted to [[United States declaration of war on Germany (1917)|declare war on Germany]]; Wilson had asked [[United States Congress|Congress]] for \"a [[The war to end war|war to end all wars]]\" that would \"make the world safe for democracy\".<ref>{{cite book |first=Arthur S. |last=Link |title=Woodrow Wilson and the Progressive Era, 1910\u20131917 |year=1972 |location=New York |publisher=Harper & Row |pages=252\u2013282 |isbn= }}</ref>\n\nWoodrow Wilson considered another military invasion of Veracruz and [[Tampico]] in 1917\u20131918,<ref name=\"Ernest Gruening\">{{cite book | first = Ernest | last = Gruening | year = 1968 | url = https://books.google.com/?id=VoBlAAAAMAAJ&q=occupation+president+wilson | title = Mexico and Its Heritage | page = 596 | publisher = Greenwood Press | location = U.S.}}</ref><ref name=\"Halevy\">{{cite book | first = Drew Philip | last = Halevy | year = 2000 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=WOfKxFigGSwC | title = Threats of Intervention: U. S.-Mexican Relations, 1917\u20131923 | page = 41 | publisher = iUniverse | location = U.S.| isbn = 9781469701783 }}</ref> so as to pacify the [[Isthmus of Tehuantepec|Tehuantepec Isthmus]] and Tampico oil fields and ensure their continued production during the civil war,<ref name=\"Halevy\" /><ref name=\"MeyerL-p45\">{{cite book | first = Lorenzo | last = Meyer | year = 1977 | url = https://books.google.com/?id=PAy1AAAAIAAJ&q=lansing+tehuantepec | title = Mexico and the United States in the Oil Controversy, 1917\u20131942 | page = 45 | publisher = University of Texas Press | location = U.S.| isbn = 9780292750326 }}</ref> but this time the relatively new Mexican President [[Venustiano Carranza]] threatened to destroy the oil fields in the event that the Marines landed there.<ref name=\"Stephen Haber\">{{cite book | first1 = Stephen | last1 = Haber | first2 = Noel | last2 = Maurer | first3 = Armando | last3 = Razo | year = 2003 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=znZ8Y8lO7_4C&q=+%22burning+of+the+oil+fields%22#v=snippet&q=%22burning%20of%20the%20oil%20fields%22&f=false | title = The Politics of Property Rights: Political Instability, Credible Commitments, and Economic Growth in Mexico, 1876\u20131929 | page = 201 | publisher = Cambridge University Press | location = UK| isbn = 9780521820677 }}</ref><ref name=\"MeyerL-p44\">Meyer, Lorenzo (1977), [https://books.google.com/books?id=PAy1AAAAIAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=destroy+fields p. 44]</ref>\n\n==Japanese response==\nThe government of Japan, another nation mentioned in the Zimmerman Telegram, was already involved in World War I, on the side of the Allied Powers against Germany. The Japanese government later released a statement that Japan was not interested in changing sides and attacking America.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://historyguy.com/zimmerman_telegram.htm | title = Zimmerman Telegram: What Was The Zimmerman Telegram, and How Did It Affect World War One? | date = | first = Roger | last = Lee | work = The History Guy | access-date = 27 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Autograph discovery==\nIn October 2005, it was reported that an original typescript of the decoded Zimmermann Telegram had recently been discovered by an unnamed historian who was researching and preparing an official history of the United Kingdom's [[Government Communications Headquarters]] (GCHQ). The document is believed to be the actual telegram shown to the American ambassador in London in 1917. Marked in Admiral Hall's handwriting at the top of the document are the words: \"This is the one handed to Dr Page and exposed by the President.\" Since many of the secret documents in this incident had been destroyed, it had previously been assumed that the original typed \"decrypt\" was gone forever. However, after the discovery of this document, the GCHQ official historian said: \"I believe that this is indeed the same document that Balfour handed to Page.\"<ref>{{cite news |ref= Fenton |last= Fenton |first= Ben |work= The Telegraph |location= London |date= 17 October 2005 |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1500812/Telegram-that-brought-US-into-Great-War-is-found-found.html  |title= Telegram that brought US into Great War is Found Found }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Germany|Mexico|World War I|United States}}\n*[[American entry into World War I]]\n*[[Imperial German plans for the invasion of the United States]]\n*[[Mexico in World War I]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{Moreinline|section|date=July 2018}}\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |ref= Beesly|last= Beesly |first= Patrick |author-link=Patrick Beesly |year= 1982 |title= Room 40: British Naval Intelligence, 1914\u20131918 |location= New York |publisher= Harcourt, Brace, Jovanovich |isbn= 0-15-178634-8}}\n*{{cite book |ref= Boghardt |last= Boghardt |first= Thomas |author-link= Thomas Boghardt|date= November 2003 |title= The Zimmermann Telegram: Diplomacy, Intelligence and The American Entry into World War I |series= Working Paper Series |url= http://cges.georgetown.edu/docs/docs_working_papers_page/working_paper_boghardt_6-04.pdf |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060902235946/http://cges.georgetown.edu/docs/Docs_Working_Papers_Page/Working_Paper_Boghardt_6-04.pdf |archivedate= September 2, 2006 |publisher= The BMW Center for German and European Studies, [[Edmund A. Walsh School of Foreign Service]], [[Georgetown University]] |location= Washington DC |id= 6-04}}; 35pp\n* {{cite book | last = Boghardt | first = Thomas | title = The Zimmermann Telegram: Intelligence, Diplomacy, and America's Entry into World War I | year = 2012 | page = 319| isbn = 978-1612511481 }}\n* {{cite book |ref= Capozzola |last=Capozzola |first=Christopher |date= 2008 |title=Uncle Sam Wants You: World War I and the Making of the Modern American Citizen |location=Oxford |publisher=Oxford Scholarship Online |isbn=9780195335491|url=http://www.oxfordscholarship.com/view/10.1093/acprof:oso/9780195335491.001.0001/acprof-9780195335491}}\n*{{cite book |ref= Hopkirk |author-link= Peter Hopkirk |last= Hopkirk |first= Peter |year= 1994 |title= On Secret Service East of Constantinople |location= Oxford |publisher= [[Oxford University Press]] |isbn= 0-19-280230-5}}\n*{{cite book |ref= Massie |author-link= Robert Massie |last= Massie |first= Robert K.  |title= [[Castles of Steel]] |publisher= Vintage Books |location= London |year= 2007 |isbn= 978-0-09-952378-9}}\n*{{cite book |ref= Pommerin |last= Pommerin |first= Reiner |year= 1996 |chapter= Reichstagsrede Zimmermanns (Auszug), 30. M\u00e4rz 1917 |title= 'Quellen zu den deutsch-amerikanischen Beziehungen |location= Darmstadt |publisher= Wissenschaftliche Buchgesellschaft Vol. 1 |pages= 213\u201316}}\n*{{cite news|ref= Singh |author1=Singh, Simon|authorlink1=Simon Singh|title=The Zimmermann Telegraph|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/historical-notes-184-kings-road-tighnabruaich-1117153.html|accessdate=14 August 2014|work=The Independent|publisher=Independent Print Limited|date=8 September 1999|archiveurl=http://simonsingh.net/media/articles/maths-and-science/the-zimmermann-telegram/|archivedate=1999}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |ref= Bernstorff |last= Bernstorff |first= Count Johann Heinrich |year= 1920 |title= My Three Years in America |location= New York |publisher= Scribner |pages= 310\u201311}}\n*{{cite journal | last = Bridges | first = Lamar W. | title = Zimmermann telegram: reaction of Southern, Southwestern newspapers | journal = Journalism & Mass Communication Quarterly | year = 1969 | volume = 46 | issue = 1 | pages = 81\u201386 | doi=10.1177/107769906904600112}}\n*{{cite book |last= Dugdale |first= Blanche |year= 1937 |title= Arthur James Balfour |location= New York |publisher= Putnam |at=  Vol. II, pp.&nbsp;127\u2013129}}\n*{{cite book |last= Hendrick |first= Burton J. |origyear=1925 |year= 2003 |title= The Life and Letters of Walter H. Page |publisher= [[Kessinger Publishing]] |isbn= 0-7661-7106-X}}\n*{{cite book |last= Kahn |first= David  |origyear= 1967 |year= 1996 |title= The Codebreakers |location= New York |publisher= Macmillan}}\n*{{cite book |last= Winkler |first= Jonathan Reed |year= 2008 |title= Nexus: Strategic Communications and American Security in World War I |location= Cambridge, MA |publisher= [[Harvard University Press]] |isbn= 978-0-674-02839-5}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisource|Zimmermann Telegram}}\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://texashistory.unt.edu/young/educators/wwI/index.shtml Failed Diplomacy: the Zimmermann Telegram]\n*[http://www.ourdocuments.gov/doc.php?doc=60 Our Documents \u2013 Zimmermann Telegram (1917)]\n*[http://germannavalwarfare.info/indexMEX.htm GermanNavalWarfare.info], Some Original Documents from the British Admiralty, [[Room 40]], regarding the Zimmermann-/Mexico Telegram: Photocopies from [[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|The National Archives]], Kew, Richmond, 